  <!-- Síntesis de la actividad -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="synthesis-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Have 2–3 students share a rectangle for each expression.</li>
      <li><p>For each student sample ask:</p><ul>
<li>
<q>¿Cómo corresponde el área de este rectángulo a la expresión?</q> (I see 4 equal groups of 6 because each row has 6 squares. I see 4 equal groups because each column has 6 squares.)</li>
</ul>
      </li>
      <li><p>Consider asking:</p><ul>
<li>
<q>¿Alguien dibujó un rectángulo diferente para esta expresión?</q></li>
</ul>
      </li>
      <li>Display a rectangle that two students oriented differently.</li>
      <li>
        <q>¿Cómo pueden corresponder estos dos rectángulos a la misma expresión?</q>  (They have the same number of squares. They have the same side lengths, just switched. I see the groups in the rows in the first rectangle and in the columns in the second rectangle.)
      </li>
      <li>Display the 3-by-5 rectangle and descriptions from the launch in the first activity.</li>
      <li>
        <q>¿Cuál de las maneras de describir un rectángulo fue la que más les ayudó a dibujar rectángulos en esta actividad?</q>  (It was helpful to describe how many rows were in the rectangle and how many squares were in each row. It was helpful to think about one factor as the number of columns and the other factor as the number of squares in each column.)
      </li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>


